    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for the candidate service components [carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user] do the following steps:\n1) For each combination of cmdb_id and kpi_name (use all kpi_name values present for those cmdb_ids), compute the global P95 threshold from the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window when computing P95).\n2) Then filter the metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 03:47:24 to 2024-01-19 04:17:24 UTC and for each cmdb_id-kpi_name group compute: total_rows_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window where anomaly is value >= P95 for that group, and earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (if any). Also compute the maximum value in-window and the P95 threshold breach ratio = (max_value - p95)/p95 (use NaN if p95==0).\n3) Return a compact table (limit to top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, total_rows_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, breach_ratio. Sort rows by anomaly_count_in_window desc then breach_ratio desc. If no rows found for a component-KPI, still include it with zeros/NaN.\nDo not compute any plots and do not include trace or error_logs yet. Keep output concise."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95 thresholds per component-KPI (using full metric series) and inspected the incident window. Key findings: (1) payment/socket shows 25/25 in-window points flagged (p95=5.0) but breach_ratio==0 — values equal the P95, so not a dramatic spike. (2) Many services (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) show the 'error' KPI flagged because p95==0 and in-window values are 0 — these are not informative (false positives due to p95==0). (3) orders latency-50 and latency-90 show the largest relative breaches (breach_ratio ~6.6 and ~2.1) with earliest anomalies around 2024-01-19 03:52:00 UTC, but only 2 anomaly points each (short-lived). (4) catalogue cpu, some socket KPIs, and user/cpu show small numeric breaches but low severity. Traces and error_logs are empty, so further localization must rely on log.csv. We should now analyze log.csv using the same threshold -> filter -> anomaly-count approach for candidate services [carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user] to see which service shows meaningful log anomalies in the incident window and to help identify the root-cause resource/reason.",
