    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, focus on cmdb_id == 'orders'. For each kpi_name available for orders: 1) compute the global P95 using the full series (do NOT filter by incident window). 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 03:47:24 — 2024-01-19 04:17:24 UTC and compute: total_rows_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (if any), max_value_in_window, breach_ratio = (max_value - p95)/p95 (NaN if p95==0). 3) Additionally, identify consecutive anomaly segments within the window (consecutive minutes where value >= p95): for each segment return start_timestamp_utc, end_timestamp_utc, length_in_minutes. Limit reported segments to the first 5 segments per KPI. Return a compact table (one row per orders-kpi) with columns: kpi_name, p95, total_rows_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc, max_value_in_window, breach_ratio, segments (as a short list). Sort rows by breach_ratio desc then anomaly_count desc. Limit output to all orders KPIs only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 thresholds for all candidate services and inspected the incident window. Traces and error_logs are empty. Metric analysis found the strongest, high-severity anomaly in the orders service: latency-50 shows a very large relative breach (breach_ratio ≈ 6.6) with earliest anomaly at 2024-01-19 03:52:00 UTC; latency-90 for orders also elevated (breach_ratio ≈ 2.1) at the same time. Other KPIs for orders (cpu, mem, socket, workload) only show small numeric breaches (breach_ratio << 0.1) and very few anomalous minutes. Many services show log.error_count anomalies but those are driven by p95 == 0 and in-window zeros (not informative). log.row_count shows only small increases around ~03:58. Catalogue has a small latency-90 increase around 03:51 but its breach is much smaller. Given (a) orders shows the largest relative latency spike starting ~03:52 and (b) resource KPIs (cpu/mem/diskio) for orders do not indicate resource exhaustion at the same time, the most likely root cause is a service-level latency issue in the orders component rather than CPU/memory/disk saturation. Because socket metrics do not show a strong, simultaneous spike for orders at the same timestamp (socket anomalies appear later and are minor), the likely failure reason is network-related latency (e.g., network latency or transient packet delays) affecting orders' responses rather than CPU/memory or disk I/O exhaustion. However, to be confident, we should confirm that latency KPIs across all candidate services show orders as the top outlier by breach magnitude and earliest occurrence.",
